"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"841E3500938F11EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":6,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"465C7DC2939011EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":4,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":28.5,"unit":"Micromolar (\u00b5M)","title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"84371EC0939011EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":5,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":9.5,"unit":"Micromolar (\u00b5M)","title":""}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"149F1660939211EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":6,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":4,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"192C9D04939211EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":7,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-20,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054731,"guid":"1A217E7C939211EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":8,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-80,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054732,"guid":"76D2FB53939211EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":9,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":4,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054733,"guid":"76D2FBD8939211EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":10,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-20,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054734,"guid":"375DA120939311EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":11,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":2,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}},{"id":1054735,"guid":"7D796738939311EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":12,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-20,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054736,"guid":"6F770C90939311EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":13,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-80,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":938148,"guid":"8755E060938F11EAA4BA150272D60A85","previous_id":938147,"previous_guid":"67373860938F11EAA4BA150272D60A85","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"18AD9228E1EC4E0EA4DA51E3AEC91679","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"991FB012169D4F8E8F89D2ED054ADE73","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Injection<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Inject <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> in the yolk at the single-cell stage, before the cell inflates.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">You are injecting:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> = <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> Cas9<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> = <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> sgRNA<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If 3x; each sgRNA is <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> = <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">In my experience, the solution left a black stain in the yolk after a few seconds when injected successfully, so I did not use a dye.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If using multiple needles (for instance when injecting scrambled RNPs for control), try leaving the needle you are not using on ice on the side.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"C1A45ED0939011EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"EB96BE40939011EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":28.5,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"F7D38670939011EAA4BA150272D60A85","order_id":4,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":4700,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"00AA7FD1939111EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":5,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":28.5,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"00AA8060939111EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":6,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1000,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"12D0DE01939111EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":7,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":9.5,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054731,"guid":"12D0DE8B939111EA95850A58A9FEAC2A","order_id":8,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":333,"unit":null,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1068029,"guid":"83B863A01DCE11EBB2D699DD28839602","previous_id":938148,"previous_guid":"8755E060938F11EAA4BA150272D60A85","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E7850A28FB054AB2A9D9AF8F2EED638C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5C77D3645EB9434CA977B0671B3FCB31","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;\">1- Can you confirm you inject in the yolk? Is it not better to inject in the cell?<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Yes, we have always injected in the yolk. We simply aim to inject in the centre of the yolk. Wu et al., 2018 (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1016\/j.devcel.2018.06.003\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">10.1016\/j.devcel.2018.06.003<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>) looked at yolk vs cell injections in great detail. Among others, they found that the RNPs are rapidly transferred to the cell. It is possible that injecting directly in the cell would create slightly more mutations. However, mutagenesis is not a limiting factor in our experience. We would actually be slightly more worried about generating <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">too many <\/span><span>double-strand breaks, especially when targeting multiple genes at once. Most importantly, yolk injections are much quicker, which means 1) all the eggs are injected rapidly just after they are laid; 2) higher Ns can be achieved, which is especially useful for experiments where a population of F0 knockouts need to be phenotyped.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;\">2- My gene has a single\/two exons, how should I proceed?<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>We would simply place all three target sites on the same exon (or two on one exon). In the publication, this was the case for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">mab21l2<\/span><span>. You can read more about this in the Author response (question 7). Try to spread out the target sites  as much as possible, especially avoiding overlap between each crRNA binding site\/PAM sequence. This is to avoid as much as possible situations where one RNP mutates the binding site\/PAM of another RNP.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;\">3- Did any F0 knockout failed to replicate a stable mutant line phenotype?<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">At the time of writing this protocol, we have targeted 13 genes and replicated all expected phenotypes. All examples are presented in the publication.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;\">4- In vitro transcribed sgRNA are more economic \u2013\u00a0is it necessary to use synthetic crRNA and tracrRNA?<\/span><span><\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Yes. It is highly likely that synthetic RNAs (i.e. not in vitro transcribed) are necessary for the success of the method. You can find an explanation and references in Author response (question 8).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;\">5- It is more economic to use Cas9 mRNA \u2013\u00a0is it necessary to use Cas9 protein?<\/span><span><\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Yes. We think it is unlikely that the method would work as well with Cas9 mRNA. You can find an explanation and references in Author response (question 2).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;\">6- How early should I inject?<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>We think it is crucial to inject <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">very<\/span><span> early, i.e. at the single-cell stage before the cell inflates. The cell should still be flat, wrapped around the yolk. I generally set everything up for injections (calibrate the needles, etc), then remove the divider of a few breeding boxes and wait for 7\u20138 minutes next to it, then collect the eggs,  put the divider back, inject these eggs. All the eggs are generally injected within the first 20 minutes after they are laid. If for any reason some eggs have started inflating or dividing, I start over with the next clutch. This may be eased a little if the studied phenotype does not require maximum penetrance.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#9b9b9b","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Remember to cite the publication if you use this protocol!<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Get in touch for questions<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">twitter \u2013\u00a0@francois_kroll<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">email \u2013\u00a0francois@kroll.be<\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1605196573}